<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species was originally published as a variety of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Allium senescens" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="senescens">Allium senescens</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S.O.Yu, S.Lee &amp; W.T.Lee" authorityYear="1981" class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Allium senescens subsp. var. var. minus" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="senescens" subSpecies="var." variety="minus">Allium senescens var. minus</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘minor’">'minor'</normalizedToken>
. However, this Korean endemic taxon has been revealed as a biologically distinct species. It is remarkably well distinguished from its relatives of the section 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Allium" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Rhiziridum">Allium Rhiziridum</taxonomicName>
by having much narrower and shorter leaf blades and scapes, smaller floral organs, non-exerted filaments and earlier flowering season from May to late July (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="T3" captionText="Table 3. Comparison of major characters of Allium section Rhizirideum in South Korea and northeastern China." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/AF867E5A3B86068A65AC72BC5A6CFB14" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableUuid="AF867E5A3B86068A65AC72BC5A6CFB14">3</tableCitation>
; Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Comparative photographs of the inflorescence, cross-section of leaf and scape, flower, and tepal and filament arrangement of Allium section Rhizirdeum in South Korea and northeastern China A-E A. dumebuchum (H. J. Choi 201008 - 001) F-J A. spirale (H. J. Choi 191010 - 01) K-O A. spurium (H. J. Choi 200831 - 01) P-T A. minus (H. J. Choi 080063) U-Y A. senescens (H. J. Choi 080119)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.176.63378.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/531582" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12228-009-9124-6" author="Choi, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="199 - 205" refId="B1" refString="Choi, HJ, Oh, BU, 2010. A new species and a new combination of Allium sect. Rhizirideum (Alliaceae) from northeastern China and Korea. Brittonia 62 (3): 199 - 205, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12228-009-9124-6" title="A new species and a new combination of Allium sect. Rhizirideum (Alliaceae) from northeastern China and Korea." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12228-009-9124-6" volume="62" year="2010">Choi and Oh 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.2011.01166.x" author="Choi, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="153 - 211" refId="B2" refString="Choi, HJ, Oh, BU, 2011. A partial revision of Allium (Amaryllidaceae) in Korea and north-eastern China. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 167 (2): 153 - 211, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.2011.01166.x" title="A partial revision of Allium (Amaryllidaceae) in Korea and north-eastern China." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.2011.01166.x" volume="167" year="2011">Choi and Oh 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Considering these major differences, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12228-009-9124-6" author="Choi, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="199 - 205" refId="B1" refString="Choi, HJ, Oh, BU, 2010. A new species and a new combination of Allium sect. Rhizirideum (Alliaceae) from northeastern China and Korea. Brittonia 62 (3): 199 - 205, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12228-009-9124-6" title="A new species and a new combination of Allium sect. Rhizirideum (Alliaceae) from northeastern China and Korea." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12228-009-9124-6" volume="62" year="2010">Choi and Oh (2010)</bibRefCitation>
proposed the rank of species for this taxon as more appropriate than that of variety. Although it is cultivated as a vegetable in South Korea, its natural populations are only known from the type locality so far (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Distribution map of Allium dumebuchum and its related species section Allium dumebuchum Rhizirideum in Korea and northeastern China (revised from Sinitsyna et al. 2016)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.176.63378.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/531586" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5</figureCitation>
). However, this species proved to have been extinct in the natural habitat in this study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
